note: Garrett was excellent in Week 4, racking up three solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. He is up to four sacks on the season and has recorded a sack in three of his four contests (he was injured in the contest he failed to register a sack). Continue to treat him as a top-five DL option for Week 5 against Washington.

Nick Bosa was excellent in Week 4, racking up four solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Bosa is up to three sacks on the season and remains a DL1 play for Week 5 against the Arizona Cardinals. Start him with confidence.

Sweat showed up in Week 4, tallying two solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Sweat has now recorded a sack in back-to-back weeks and is safe to trust as a DL1 option for a pus Week 5 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Chris Jones was excellent in Week 4, tallying three solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. He has been a non factor when he is not getting sacks thus far, but is strong enough against both the run and the pass that Jones should start to produce even when he is not taking down the quarterback. Tap him as a DL2/DT1 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Heyward was excellent in Week 4, registering two solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Heyward now has a sack in back-to-back weeks and is firmly entrenched as a top-10 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Dorance was excellent in Week 4, racking up three solos, two assists, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Armstrong has played roughly 60 percent of the snaps for Washington and after 0.5 sacks last week, appears to be heating up just in time for the byes. Tap him as a DL3/4 option where needed.

YaYa Diaby showed up in Week 4, tallying two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He had not much done in the way of counting stats before this outing, so those in deeper leagues should add him to watch lists or even benches but keep him out of starting lineups. He has upside and potential, but more consistency is needed before starting him as an option during a light bye.

Jonathan Allen showed up in Week 4, tallying four solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Allen has been a disappointment through four weeks of the season, as he had three solos and zero sacks total coming into the weekend. Still, he is a DT1 option and should be treated as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Cleveland Browns. Those looking for a DL4 should look elsewhere.

Collins was excellent in Week 4, registering two solos, one assist, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. He has recorded a sack in two straight weeks and is worth a start as a DT1 option for those dealing with byes or injuries. Treat him as a top-15 DT option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Fiske showed up in Week 4, recording two solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. The sack was the first of his career and should lead to an expanded role, but as an odd front end, he is going to be inconsistent. Leave him on benches for Week 5.

Dayo showed up in Week 4, racking up one solo, two assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Dayo is not much of an option outside of heavy byes but is worth a look for those in a pinch for Week 5, thanks to a plus matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Givens went bonkers in Week 4, racking up two solos, one assist, 2.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. He is up to 3.5 sacks on the season and should be on radars for those in DT leagues. He is not much of an option outside of DT leagues, but 3.5 sacks in three games makes him worth a DL4/flex look for those in deeper 11 v 11 leagues. Add and start Givens where needed.

Vita Vea showed up in Week 4, notching two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. The sack was just his first of the season, but Vea remains a DT1 play for Week 5 and beyond. With that said, he is nothing more than bye week filler for those outside of DT leagues.

Wise was excellent in Week 4, recording two solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Wise has recorded a sack in back-to-back weeks and makes for an intriguing DL4 play for Week 5, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Peyton Tuner showed up in Week 4, notching two solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. The sack was his first of the season, so keep the rotational edge rusher on benches or the wire for the time being. The talent is there for a stash in redraft leagues, but we need to see consistent production before plugging him into lineups.

Spillane continues to produce at an elite level for his fantasy managers, most recently notching nine solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. He has at least seven solos in every game this year and should be viewed as a top-10 option until further notice.

Warner was excellent in Week 5, recording four solos, three assists, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. Warner is an elite play every single Sunday and should be treated as a top-five option for Week 5, thanks to a plus matchup against Kyler Murray and the Arizona Cardinals.

Speed went off in Week 4, racking up 12 solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Speed has been elite to start the 2024 season and has at least six solos in each contest. Tap him as an LB1 for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Wagner was excellent in Week 4, tallying seven solos, four assists, 0.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. He has recorded at least five solos in every game this season, putting him firmly in the top-15 mix. Treat him as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Zaire did Zaire things, racking up six solos and three assists against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Zaire remains a top-three option weekly and now has a case for the unquestioned top spot with Foye Oluokun on IR. Start Zaire everywhere as a top three IDP option, regardless of position.

Kendricks was at it again in Week 4, tallying six solos and seven assists. He has at least five solos in three of his four contests, posting at least eight total tackles in each. Tap Kendricks as a top-20 option for a tasty Week 5 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Cashman was excellent in Week 4, tallying six solos, five assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Cashman has been inconsistent in the solo department but has still put up LB2 numbers for fantasy managers. Tap him as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the New York Jets. Add and start Cashman wherever available.

Kyzir was solid in Week 4, notching six solos and three assists. Kyzir stays busy with total tackles, but that does not always translate into solo production. Still, Kyzir has been as consistent as they come for IDP managers through three weeks of the season and should post another LB2 level outing this week against the San Francisco 49ers. Start Kyzir everywhere as a top-25 option.

Okereke was solid in Week 4, tallying five solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Okereke has been a disappointment (IDP wise) through four weeks of the season and should be viewed as more LB2 than LB1 until he starts to produce at a level more commensurate with expectations.

Lavonte went off in Week 4, tallying five solos, three assists, two sacks, two tackles for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Despite sporadic solo production, Lavonte has been a top-15 option through four weeks of the season. Treat him as such for Week 5, despite a neutral at best matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

JOK was busy again in Week 4, racking up six solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. He has recorded six solos in three of his four contests and is a strong upside LB2 option during the byes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against Washington.

Quincy was busy on Sunday, tallying five solos, two assists, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. He has at least five solos in every contest this season and should continue to be treated as a top-20 option.

Pratt was excellent in Week 4, tallying six solos, three assists, and one pass defended. He has recorded six or more solos in three straight games and is a high upside LB2 option for Week 5's showdown with the Baltimore Ravens. Tap Pratt as a top-20 option.

Quay was excellent in Week 4, racking up six solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Walker has recorded six or more solos in three of his four games this season and should continue to be treated as an LB2 option. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Luvu had a strong Week 4, posting five solos, two assists, 0.5 sacks, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Luvu has been inconsistent thus far and cannot be trusted as anything more than an LB3/4 despite the byes and a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Dorian was excellent in Week 4, racking up five solos, seven assists, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Williams has at least five solos in every game this season and has quietly entered the LB2 conversation. Treat him as such for Week 5, thanks to a plus matchup against the Houston Texans.

Andersen went wild in Week 4, racking up 10 solos, seven assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. He has at least five solos in every game this season and needs to be treated as an LB2 until he cools down. He is dealing with an ankle injury, so prepare your FAAB bid accordingly. Treat him as an LB2 for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. Add and start Andersen everywhere.

McFadden has a firm hold on the linebacker role next to Bobby Okreke and has responded with five or more solos in each of his last three contests. He played 75 percent of the snaps, with Darius Muasau playing zero and Isaiah Simmons playing 25 percent. Neither player appears to be a threat to McFadden's laying time going forward. He is a strong LB3 option who can double as an LB2 play during the heavy byes but with just four teams on break for Week 5, treat him as an LB3 for a neutral matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Rozeboom was excellent in Week 4, posting six solos and five assists. This was his first contest above the four solo mark, putting him on the radar as an LB3/4 option now that the byes are here. Rozeboom should be rostered in all competitive leagues, at least during the byes. Tap Rozeboom as an LB3 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

The Cowboys are planning to be without Micah Parsons for Week 5. Marshawn Kneeland and Carl Lawson are expected to draw the starts, but it will remain a rotation, even with Parsons and Demarcus Lawrence sidelined.

Wallace appears set for an expanded role in the wake of the Shaq Thompson injury and is expected to draw the bulk of the snaps next to Josey Jewell. Wallace played 37 percent of the snaps in Week 4 and should jump up to north of 60 percent for the rest of the season (barring a free agent addition). He didn't do much with his expanded Week 4 role but should flash given a whole week to prepare as a starter. Wallace has LB2 upside and talent but should be viewed as more of an LB4/flex option until he shows some consistency in terms of snaps and production. Still, for those in redraft leagues, Wallace is a potential depth chart changer. Make the add everywhere possible.

Overshown was excellent in Week 4, stacking six solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Overshown has completely overtaken Damone Clark in Mike ZImmer's defense, playing 86 percent of the snaps in Week 4 while Clark played just seven percent. Overshwon is a solid lB3 option during the byes and should be considered an upside option for Week 5, thanks to a plus matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Add and start Overshown where needed.

Sherwood is an IDP option as long as CJ Mosley remains sidelined. The Jets had high hopes for Sherwood before Quincy Williams ran away with the job. Mosley is dealing with a toe injury and did not practice at all leading up to Week 4, so Sherwood could indeed be in line for at least one more start for the Jets. He was solid in Week 3, tallying six solos, one assist, and a tackle for loss and has two contests with six or more solos since Mosley was injured. It is better to view him as an LB4/flex, but with the byes here, he is more than serviceable as an upside LB3 play. Act accordingly.

Spector was excellent in Week 4, tallying four solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Baylon has been solid filling in for the injured Terell Bernard and should be rostered in all competitive leagues until he returns. Tap Spector as an LB3 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Drue was excellent in Week 4, racking up seven solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Tranquill dropped to flex territory after a slow start to the season but remains in play now that the byes weeks are here, and he seems to be heating up. Tap him as an LB3/4 for a neutral Week 5 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Ventrell stepped up in the absences of Foye Oluokun and Devin Lloyd, racking up eight solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. He should soak up tackles in the Jaguars scheme as is a sneaky LB2 play for as long as Lloyd is sidelined. Miller projects as more of an LB3/flex when Lloyd returns. Add and start Ventrell wherever needed.

It's time we all start taking Kyle Van Noy seriously. Yes, he is still playing less than 50 percent of the snaps in Baltimore's edge rusher rotation, but he is up to six sacks on the season and is set to shatter the career high nine sacks he set last season. Van Noy recorded two solos, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble in Week 4 against the Buffalo Bills. He is riding a six game sack streak in which he has recorded two sacks in each. His snap share will keep him as a DL3 option outside of the heavy byes, but he needs to be rostered and started in all competitive leagues. Add Van Noy everywhere.

Brisker was excellent in Week 4, racking up eight solos, one sack, two tackles for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. He has hit five or more solos just twice this season but does have 20 total solos through four contests. This game was a step in the right direction for the former IDP dynamo and helps put him in the top-15 conversation for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Kyle Hamilton was excellent in Week 4, tallying six solos, one assist, and one fumble recovery. Hamilton has recorded five or more solos in each of his last three games and is putting up numbers expected of a DB1. Continue to treat him as one for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Budda was at it again in Week 4, racking up 10 solos and four assists against Washington. He has turned back the hands of time through four weeks of the season and has been a force as a DB1 option. There is no way to know if he can continue to produce at this level for the rest of the season, but he has remarked that this is the most fun he has ever had in a defensive scheme, so perhaps that is translating to IDP production. Whatever the case, Budda is a DB1 option for Week 5 against the San Francisco 49ers.

Lake continues to impress for the Rams, racking up four solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Lake is a DB1 until further notice and should be treated as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Cross continues to impress for the Colts, most recently registering seven solos, one assist, and one forced fumble. Cross has six or more solos in every game this season and is up to 31 solos on the season. Cross is a DB1 until further notice and should be treated as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Minkah was excellent in Week 4, tallying six solos and three assists. Minkah has five or more solos in three of his four contests and is an elite DB1 play for Sunday Night Football against the Dallas Cowboys. Fire him up as a top-12 option.

We have another Bynum sighting. Bynum finally made some noise in Week 4, registering sic solos, one assist, two passes defended, and one fumble recovery. Bynum seems to be getting his groove back after a slow start to the season and can once again be counted as a top-15 option going forward. Treat him as just that for a plus Week 5 matchup against the New York Jets.

Blackmon continues to produce for the Colts, this time adding three solos, three assists, 0.5 sacks, and one fumble recovery to his ledger. Blackmon has been producing at a DB1 level and should be treated as a top-15 option for Week 5.

Chinn was excellent in Week 4, notching seven solos, three assists, and one forced fumble. Chinn has stepped up his production over the last two weeks and has played nearly every snap, putting him back on the IDP radar. He should be rostered in all competitive leagues and makes for an intriguing DB3 option for Week 5, thanks to a tasty matchup against a struggling Deshaun Watson and the Cleveland Browns. Add and start Chinn wherever possible.

Adams was excellent in Week 4, tallying five solos, six assists, and two tackles for loss. It was a bounce back performance for Adams, who was a standout in the opener before going quiet over the last two weeks. Adams remains more DB3 than DB2 for now but has flashed obvious DB2 upside. Start Adams as an elite DB3 play for Week 5, thanks to a plus matchup against the Minnesota Vikings.

DeShon Elliott was excellent in Week 4, tallying eight solos, four assists, and one forced fumble. DeShon has been solid through four weeks of the season and is someone to consider as a depth option during the byes. Add and start him as a DB3/4 ahead of a plus Week 5 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Woods was excellent in Week 4, tallying seven solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Woods has been inconsistent but is on the IDP radar now that the byes are here, and he is playing well. He has a plus matchup set for Week 5 against the Chicago Bears and has four more plus matchups after that. He makes for a solid DB4/flex/bye week filler for those in deeper leagues. Make the add wherever needed.

Nubin was excellent in Week 4, racking up six solos, two assists, and one forced fumble. Nubin had been quiet since Week 1 but now has five or more solos in two of his four contests this season. Inconsistency is to be expected from a rookie, but Nubin has more than proved that he is starter worthy in three DB leagues. Tap him as an upside DB3 play for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

IPM was excellent in his first career start, racking up four solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Pola-Mao is slated to start for the rest of the season with Marcus Epps (knee) suffering a season ending injury and should be rostered as a DB3/4/bye week filler in deeper leagues. He flashed his versatility in Week 4 and should be able to increase the counting stats once he gets more comfortable. Add IPM wherever possible ahead of an excellent Week 5 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Vonn Bell made some noise in Week 4, notching three solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. The solo production has been less than ideal, but Bell does have at least six total tackles in every contest this season. Treat him as a DB4/flex option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Peppers flashed in Week 4, racking up three solos, four assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Peppers should be left on benches (or the wire) for Week 5 despite his standout production in Week 4, as he has yet to show any consistency and has yet to surpass three solos all season. He may be worth a look during the heavier byes if he can start to heat up, but IDP managers should look elsewhere for Week 5, despite a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Locke showed up in Week 4, tallying eight solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. It was by far Locke's best fantasy game of the season and is hopefully the start of more consistent play for the popular offseason breakout candidate. Locke should absolutely be rostered in all competitive leagues, but you cannot blame anyone who got impatient after the first three weeks of the season. Tap Locke as an upside DB3 for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Ji'Ayir was excellent in Week 4, racking up five solos, three assists, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Brown has been a massive IDP disappointment but pops back onto the radar due to his strong performance coinciding with the start of the byes. He is a DB4/flex option for Week 5 against Arizona.

Moehrig was excellent in Week 4, tallying four solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. He has recorded four or more solos in each of the last three weeks and is a DB3 option for Week 5, thanks to a tasty matchup against the Denver Broncos. Start Moehrig everywhere.
